The principle of detection of the immunoassay system developed in this study is illustrated in Fig. 6

                        . The two specifics bio-probe conjugates; AntiXoo-GQDs and AntiXoo-AuNPs were introduced as an energy donor (fluorophore) and energy acceptor (quencher) in a homogenous reaction solution to form an aggregation of immunocomplex binding with Xoo cells. In the reaction solution containing Xoo cells, the probe conjugates randomly self-recognized the target cell surface through the immunoreaction of antibody-antigen binding. The self-assembled-aggregation of AntiXoo-GQDs/Xoo/AntiXoo-AuNPs immunocomplex induced formation of the ground-state non-fluorescent complex that describes a static quenching mechanism. The proximity interaction of surface plasmon AuNPs and GQDs in the immuno-complex quenched the fluorescence intensity as the electronic excitation energy of GQDs transferred to AuNPs via a through-space dipole-dipole interaction between GQDs-AuNPs pairs. When this immuno-complex absorbed light at excitation 400 nm, it immediately returns to the ground state without the emission of a photon. Only the unbound GQDs conjugate probes were emitted and the total fluorescence intensity was decreased. The fluorescence intensity of reaction assay was inversely proportional to the cell concentrations. The quenching efficiency of GQDs fluorescence signal by AuNPs provides the turn-off fluorescence system that proportional to the increase of Xoo cell concentrations. This static quenching mechanism is supported by the transmission electron microscopy imaging (Fig. 7
                        ). Fig. 7 depicts HRTEM images of the immunocomplex-aggregation binding between AntiXoo-GQDs and AntiXoo-AuNPs in the presence of Xoo cells in the homogenous reaction assay [42,43]. This provides direct evidence of the formation of the ground-state non-fluorescent complex. The immuno-binding of these conjugate probes on the surface cells leads to fluorescence quenching at Ex400 nm/Em520 nm.

Fig. 11
 shows the developed BLB symptom in the artificial inoculated rice leaves that were harvested at 5, 7, and 14 days after the inoculation (DAI). The detection of Xoo in these samples was validated with conventional methods such as indirect ELISA (developed using AntiXoo antibody) and DAS-ELISA (LOEWE kit) (Table 2
). It can be noted that the developed fluorescence assay was significantly more sensitive compared to the conventional methods for the detection of Xoo. It was found that the developed method can detect a low concentration of Xoo cells (103 CFU mL−1) as early as 5 days after infection but could not be detected by DAS-ELISA and Indirect ELISA. For 7 DAI rice leaves, the developed method and indirect ELISA could detect Xoo cells at a concentration of 104 CFU mL−1 with a good correlation coefficient of 0.99. The detection of Xoo at 105 CFU mL−1 from the 14 DAI rice leaf was highly correlated between the three methods. The correlations coefficient of detection by the developed fluorescence assay with indirect-ELISA and DAS-ELISA were 0.99 and 0.98, respectively. By using ANOVA, P-value was less than 0.05 (P < 0.05) indicates no significant differences between the mean of the three methods used for the detection of Xoo. Hence, the developed GQDs fluorescence-based immunoassay is highly sensitive for the early detection of rice bacterial leaf blight disease and comparable with indirect-ELISA and DAS-ELISA methods.
